#
#  ffcli distinctive features:
#    - STRUCT-BASED COMMAND TREE — each subcommand is a
#      `*ffcli.Command` struct with `Name`/`ShortUsage`/
#      `ShortHelp`/`LongHelp`/`FlagSet`/`Subcommands`/`Exec`
#      fields; no chained-builder method calls (CONTRAST cobra
#      which uses both struct fields AND builder methods like
#      `cmd.AddCommand(child)`)
#    - STDLIB flag.FlagSet — each Command has its own
#      `*flag.FlagSet` (stdlib flag, NOT spf13/pflag); flags are
#      registered with stdlib `fs.String`/`Bool`/`Int`/etc.
#      INSPIRED BY R417 google/subcommands (also uses stdlib
#      flag.FlagSet) but with hierarchical subcommand-TREE vs
#      google/subcommands' FLAT registry
#    - SEPARATE PARSE() AND RUN() steps — `root.Parse(args)`
#      processes argv, descends into matched subcommand,
#      populates flag values; `root.Run(ctx)` then dispatches
#      to the matched subcommand's Exec function.  This
#      SEPARATION allows ff's config-file/env merge to run
#      BETWEEN parse and run (the killer integration with
#      peterbourgon/ff core: `ff.Parse(rootFS, args,
#      ff.WithEnvVarPrefix("HETTY"))` then `root.Run(ctx)`)
#    - CONTEXT-AWARE Exec — `Exec(ctx context.Context, args
#      []string) error` receives a context for cancellation
#      (CONTRAST cobra's `RunE func(*cobra.Command, []string)
#      error` which has no built-in context)
#    - HELP/USAGE — built-in default help renderer; `UsageFunc:
#      func(*ffcli.Command) string` field allows custom help
#      text (hetty uses this for its multi-line subcommand
#      help strings)
#    - SUBCOMMANDS field — `[]*ffcli.Command` slice; ffcli
#      auto-dispatches `tool subcmd ...` to the matching
#      Command's FlagSet for parsing, then descends recursively
#    - RECURSIVE TREE — subcommands can themselves have
#      subcommands; hetty uses this for `hetty cert install`
#      and `hetty cert uninstall` two-level nesting
#    - NO automatic --version (caller handles via
#      `fs.BoolVar(&version, "version", false, "...")` and
#      checks `if version { print(VERSION); return }` in Exec)
#    - NO env-var fallback BY ITSELF — env-var merge comes
#      from pairing with `ff.Parse(...)` from the parent ff
#      package (R363 documented separately)
#    - DESIGNED for COMPOSITION with peterbourgon/ff core —
#      the ff/ffcli pair forms a complete 12-factor-app CLI
#      stack: ff for config-merge (flag/env/file), ffcli for
#      subcommand-tree
#    - DISTRIBUTED across `peterbourgon/ff` Go module — ff,
#      ff/v3, ff/v3/ffcli, ff/v3/fftest are all sub-packages
#      of the same import path
#  Distinct from R237 Go spf13/cobra (subcommand-TREE with
#  Command structs + Run/RunE func fields; cobra is heavier with
#  pflag instead of stdlib flag, AddCommand mutating builder
#  style, and richer features like custom validators/marshalers),
#  R237 Go spf13/pflag (POSIX-flag-compat replacement for stdlib
#  flag — ffcli does NOT use pflag, sticks with stdlib flag),
#  R237 Go urfave/cli (action-callback framework), R237 Go
#  alecthomas/kingpin (chained-builder), R237 Go jessevdk/go-
#  flags (struct-tag based), R237 Go mitchellh/cli (HashiCorp
#  Terraform), R262 Go stdlib `flag` (ffcli uses this internally
#  for FlagSet), R363 Go peterbourgon/ff (ff CORE for flag/env/
#  file config merge — DISTINCT FROM ffcli which is the
#  subcommand-tree layer; ffcli pairs WITH ff for the 12-factor
#  stack), R367 Go akamensky/argparse (Python-argparse-style),
#  R408 Go pborman/getopt (POSIX-getopt(3) faithful), R411 Go
#  integrii/flaggy (package-level functional-builder), R414 Go
#  alecthomas/kong (struct-tag declarative), R417 Go google/
#  subcommands (FLAT subcommand registry with stdlib flag —
#  ffcli's CLOSEST RELATIVE in design philosophy but with
#  HIERARCHICAL tree vs google/subcommands' FLAT registry), R421
#  Go namsral/flag (stdlib flag drop-in with env-var fallback),
#  R426 Go octago/sflags (META-flag-generator).  Go documented
#  libraries so far: stdlib flag, pflag, cobra, urfave-cli,
#  kingpin, jessevdk/go-flags, mitchellh/cli, ff, akamensky/
#  argparse, pborman/getopt, flaggy, kong, google/subcommands,
#  namsral/flag, sflags, ffcli (this round)... 17 total.  ffcli's
#  distinguishing feature vs all other Go libs: ffcli is the
#  ONLY Go subcommand framework in the corpus that is
#  EXPLICITLY DESIGNED FOR COMPOSITION with a SEPARATE config-
#  merge package (ff).  ffcli's split-parse-and-run model is
#  what enables `ff.Parse(fs, args, ff.WithConfigFile(...))`
#  to inject between argv parsing and command execution.
#  ffcli's approach: STRUCT-BASED HIERARCHICAL SUBCOMMAND TREE
#  with `*ffcli.Command{Name, ShortUsage, ShortHelp, LongHelp,
#  FlagSet, Subcommands, Exec, UsageFunc}` struct + stdlib `flag.
#  FlagSet` for flag registration + SEPARATE `root.Parse(args)`
#  and `root.Run(ctx)` steps (allows ff config-merge between) +
#  CONTEXT-AWARE `Exec(ctx, args) error` handler + RECURSIVE
#  subcommand nesting + UsageFunc field for custom help renderer
#  + DESIGNED for COMPOSITION with peterbourgon/ff core +
#  INSPIRED BY google/subcommands (also uses stdlib flag) but
#  hierarchical instead of flat — corpus's **first documented
#  composition-with-config-merge Go CLI library**.  Brings cross-
#  language CLI library taxonomy variant count to 170; Go
#  ecosystem now has 17 documented CLI libraries — TYING WITH
#  RUST at the top of the cross-language taxonomy ahead of
#  TypeScript-Node (16).
